  "text": "## Rust-Servo Shared Style System Discovery\n\n### Servo's Style System Architecture\n\nServo uses a shared style system hosted in the separate `servo/stylo` repository (https://github.com/servo/stylo). The Servo workspace in `Cargo.toml` (lines 160-183) declares dependencies on external `stylo`, `selectors`, and related crates from this shared repository at revision `3b46f3ef27eb14ca276b4bf3ff041a6c43d93827`:\n\n- **selectors** (v0.35.0): The CSS selector matching engine\n- **stylo** (v0.11.0): The style engine integrating Gecko style code\n- **servo_arc**: Atomic reference counting for sharing data\n- **stylo_atoms**, **stylo_config**, **stylo_dom**, **stylo_traits**: Supporting style infrastructure\n\n#### Selectors Crate Dependencies\nThe `selectors` crate depends on:\n- bitflags, cssparser, log, rustc-hash\n- servo_arc, smallvec, to_shmem\n- phf (perfect hash function)\n\n#### Stylo Crate Dependencies  \nThe `stylo` crate (the main style engine) depends on:\n- cssparser, encoding_rs, euclid, icu_segmenter\n- itertools, indexmap, parking_lot, rayon\n- selectors, servo_arc, string_cache, url\n- And many other style-related crates\n\n### Integration in Servo Components\n\n**components/layout/Cargo.toml** (lines 49, 57-59) directly declares dependencies on:\n- `selectors` - for CSS selector matching and element traits\n- `stylo` - for computed style data and matching\n- `servo_arc` - for shared Arc types\n- `stylo_atoms`, `stylo_traits` - for style infrastructure\n\nThe layout component uses selectors via `use selectors::Element` and implements the Element trait from selectors for Servo's DOM nodes. The `components/layout/layout_impl.rs` and `components/layout/dom_traversal.rs` files extensively use selectors APIs for style matching during layout calculations.\n\n### Rust's Proc-Macro Bridge\n\nServo build scripts and procedural macros depend on Rust's proc_macro infrastructure, which is defined through a sophisticated bridge system that allows safe communication between procedural macros and the compiler.\n\n#### Core Proc-Macro Bridge Files\n\n**library/proc_macro/src/lib.rs**: The main public proc_macro library entry point that exposes TokenStream, Span, and Symbol types to macro authors. The lib.rs includes the unstable bridge module (line 41): `pub mod bridge`.\n\n**library/proc_macro/src/bridge/mod.rs**: Defines the higher-order `with_api!` macro (lines 48+) that describes the complete server RPC API for proc-macro communication. This macro enables automatic generation of type-safe Rust APIs for both client-side (procedural macros) and server-side (compiler) implementations.\n\nThe bridge defines server API operations including:\n- TokenStream manipulation (create, clone, to_string, from_str)\n- Span operations (debug, parent, source, byte_range, etc.)\n- Symbol normalization and validation\n- Literal creation and manipulation\n- Diagnostic emission\n\n**library/proc_macro/src/bridge/client.rs**: Implements client-side handle types and encoding/decoding logic for the bridge protocol.\n\n**library/proc_macro/src/bridge/server.rs**: Implements server-side implementations of the bridge API traits.\n\n#### Compiler-Side Integration\n\n**compiler/rustc_expand/src/proc_macro_server.rs**: The compiler's implementation of the proc_macro bridge server. This file imports `rustc_proc_macro::bridge` (line 14) which provides the bridge protocol implementation. It implements trait conversions between internal rustc AST types and the proc_macro bridge types (FromInternal/ToInternal traits, lines 25-31+).\n\n**compiler/rustc_proc_macro/Cargo.toml**: This crate reexports library/proc_macro/src/lib.rs as its library (line 13) to avoid creating duplicate proc_macro copies in the sysroot during bootstrap.\n\n### Servo's Procedural Macro Components\n\nServo uses Rust's proc_macro infrastructure for several build-time code generation tasks:\n\n**components/dom_struct/lib.rs**: Defines the `#[dom_struct]` procedural macro attribute (line 14) that automatically generates WebIDL DOM object implementations. This macro uses the standard `proc_macro::TokenStream` to process attributes and generate additional trait implementations for DOM objects.\n\n**components/servo_tracing/lib.rs**: Implements the `#[trace]` procedural macro for automatic tracing/debugging support, also using the standard proc_macro infrastructure.\n\n### Shared Architecture Summary\n\nThe bridge between Rust and Servo occurs at multiple levels:\n\n1. **Style System**: Servo depends on the shared `servo/stylo` repository containing `selectors` and `stylo` crates that implement CSS matching and styling\n2. **Build-Time Codegen**: Servo's procedural macros (dom_struct, servo_tracing) depend on Rust's proc_macro bridge defined in library/proc_macro/src/bridge/mod.rs\n3. **Compiler Integration**: The rustc_expand module implements the server-side of the proc_macro bridge that Servo's build scripts use\n\nThe proc_macro bridge uses a Higher-Order Macro (with_api!) pattern to automatically generate type-safe client and server implementations, enabling procedural macros to safely communicate with the compiler across potentially mismatched ABIs."
